# 🧹 Slidev Linter

Format Slidev markdown slides consistently, automatically, and predictably.

`slidev-linter` is a focused CLI for teams who want clean slide formatting rules enforced the same way locally and in CI.

## 🧭 Positioning

- `slidev build` detects common Slidev compile/render issues.
- `slidev-linter check|lint` enforces consistent formatting across already healthy markdown files.
- Recommended flow: `slidev build` -> `slidev-linter check ...` -> `slidev-linter lint ...` when fixes are needed.

## 🎯 Why Use It

- Keep deck formatting consistent across many files and contributors.
- Eliminate repetitive manual cleanup (titles, transitions, spacing).
- Run a deterministic check in CI with stable exit codes and JSON output.
- Apply fixes safely with explicit selectors (`all`, `chapter`, `range`, `file`, `pattern`).

## ✅ What It Solves

- Normalizes top-level and section slide transitions.
- Removes redundant title bold markers.
- Enforces readable spacing between titles and subtitles.
- Adds consistent spacing after slide titles where appropriate.
- Preserves idempotency: running twice should not keep changing files.

## 🚀 Install

### Recommended: global CLI via `pipx`

```bash
brew install pipx
pipx ensurepath
pipx install git+https://github.com/Th3Mouk/slidev-linter.git
```

Then run:

```bash
slidev-linter list rules
```

### Alternative: local package install

```bash
python3 -m venv .venv
./.venv/bin/pip install -U pip
./.venv/bin/pip install -e .
./.venv/bin/slidev-linter list rules
```

### Optional: npm scripts integration

Add convenient aliases in your `package.json`:

```json
{
  "scripts": {
    "lint:slides": "slidev-linter lint all --slides-dir ./slides",
    "lint:slides:check": "slidev-linter check all --slides-dir ./slides"
  }
}
```

## ⚡ Quick Start

### 1. Detect common Slidev errors

```bash
slidev build
```

### 2. Check formatting consistency (no file changes)

```bash
slidev-linter check all --slides-dir ./slides
```

### 3. Apply formatting fixes (if needed)

```bash
slidev-linter lint all --slides-dir ./slides
```

### 4. Verify CI-friendly JSON output

```bash
slidev-linter check all --slides-dir ./slides --format json
```

## 🛠️ CLI

### Commands

```bash
slidev-linter lint <selector>
slidev-linter check <selector>
slidev-linter list rules
slidev-linter list rule-sets
# Equivalent module entrypoint:
python -m slidev_linter lint <selector>
```

### Selectors

```bash
all
file <path-or-glob>
chapter <n>
range <start-end>
pattern <glob>
```

### Shared options (`lint` and `check`)

- `--slides-dir <dir>`: custom slides root (default: `./slides`)
- `--rule-set <name>`: apply one predefined rule set
- `--rules <rule...>`: apply explicit rule list
- `--format text|json`: output mode (default: `text`)

### Practical examples

```bash
# List capabilities
slidev-linter list rules
slidev-linter list rule-sets

# Target by scope
slidev-linter lint chapter 20 --slides-dir ./slides
slidev-linter lint range 20-29 --slides-dir ./slides
slidev-linter lint file 20-intro.md --slides-dir ./slides
slidev-linter check pattern "2[0-9]-*.md" --slides-dir ./slides

# Rule selection
slidev-linter lint all --slides-dir ./slides --rule-set basic_formatting
slidev-linter lint all --slides-dir ./slides --rules remove_bold_from_titles clean_transitions
```

## 📋 Rules

### Basic formatting

- `remove_bold_from_titles`: `# **Title**` -> `# Title`

### Transition rules

- `default_transition`: ensures top frontmatter transition is `slide-left`
- `section_transition`: enforces `transition: slide-left` on `layout: section` slides
- `clean_transitions`: removes misplaced/duplicated transition artifacts

### Spacing rules

- `ensure_space_between_title_subtitle`: inserts blank line between `#` and `##`
- `add_spacing_after_titles`: inserts `<p class="py-2"/>` after slide titles when relevant

## 📦 Rule Sets

- `basic_formatting`
- `advanced_formatting` (default)

If neither `--rule-set` nor `--rules` is provided, `advanced_formatting` is used.

## 📤 Output Contract

### JSON payload (`--format json`)

Each `lint` / `check` run emits one JSON object with:

- `mode`
- `selector`
- `rules_applied`
- `files_total`
- `files_changed`
- `files_unchanged`
- `errors`
- `duration_ms`
- `per_file` (`{file, changed, action, error}`)

### Exit codes

- `0`: success / clean check
- `1`: `check` found files needing changes
- `2`: usage/validation error
- `3`: runtime file I/O error

These codes are stable and intended for CI scripting.

## 🔁 CI Usage

Recommended CI sequence:

```bash
slidev build
slidev-linter check all --slides-dir ./slides
```

Autofix job step (format normalization):

```bash
slidev-linter lint all --slides-dir ./slides
```

Fixture contract in this repository:

- source fixtures: `fixtures/[0-9][0-9]-*.md`
- expected outputs: `fixtures/expected/[0-9][0-9]-*.md`

## 🧪 Developer Quickstart

```bash
python3 -m venv .venv
./.venv/bin/pip install -U pip
./.venv/bin/pip install -e ".[dev]"
./.venv/bin/ruff check .
./.venv/bin/mypy src tests
./.venv/bin/python -m pytest
./.venv/bin/python -m pytest --cov=slidev_linter --cov-report=term-missing --cov-report=xml
```

## 🔧 Customization

The linter is extensible. You can add custom rules by implementing new classes that inherit from `Rule` and define `apply(content: str) -> str`.

